--In the old days, chain armor was an enormous investment.  Expensive and time-consuming to create.  So how did they keep their chain gear shiny and rust free? (Rust-o-leum hadn't been invented yet)<br>
They would take a stout barrel and fill it half full of sand and vinegar.  Throw in the chain, and pound the top of the barrel on.  Take it to a near-by hill and roll it downhill two or three times!  RFOL!<br>
This clever idea was the world's first washing machine. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/uapo44.showPublicProfile?language=EN>apo44</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(3/1/02 2:50:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=951.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: sort of on topic</span><hr size=1> And on the side of the barrel was the word &quot;Maytag&quot;<br>
